AcceptedAnswer:
Here is an answer that uses more abstract machinery. Let $B \subset X$ be an open set homeomorphic to an open ball in $\Bbb R^n$. Let $p : X \to X / (X - B)$ be the quotient map. We have $X/(X - B) = S^n$. By the naturality of the long exact sequence, we have the commutative diagram:
$$
\require{AMScd}
\begin{CD}
H_n(X) @>\cong>> H_n(X, X - B)\\
@VVq_*V @VV\cong V \\
H_n(X / (X - B)) @>\cong>> H_n(X / (X - B), (X - B) / (X - B))
\end{CD}
$$ The upper map is an isomorphism since $X$ is orientable. The right map is an isomorphism by excision (see Hatcher's Algebraic Topology, 2.22). The lower map is an isomorphism since $(X - B) / (X - B)$ is a single point. It follows that $q_*$ is an isomorphism. Hence $q$ has degree one as desired.

Redundant_assumption:
